        body: "**INDICATIONS**\n\u2022 Distal radius and/or ulna fracture\n\u2022 Colles fracture (dorsally displaced distal radius)\n\u2022 Smith fracture (volar displaced distal radius)\n\u2022 Barton fracture\n\n**MATERIALS**\n\u2022 4-inch plaster (10 layers)\n\u2022 Stockinette, 3\u20134 layers Webril, elastic bandage\n\n**SUGAR TONG APPLICATION**\n1. Measure from dorsal MCP joints, around the elbow, to the palmar crease\n2. Apply stockinette and Webril \u2014 **extra padding over olecranon and both styloids**\n3. Apply plaster slab from dorsal hand, along dorsal forearm, around the flexed elbow (90\xB0), along volar forearm to palmar crease\n4. Mold the wrist: slight flexion (10\xB0) + ulnar deviation for Colles; neutral for Smith\n5. Secure with elastic bandage\n6. Ensure thumb and fingers remain free\n\n**A+P SPLINT ALTERNATIVE (PREFERRED)**\nInstead of wrapping around the elbow:\n1. Apply a **posterior slab** from dorsal MCP joints to proximal forearm\n2. Apply an **anterior (volar) slab** from palmar crease to proximal forearm\n3. Secure both with elastic bandage\n4. Provides equivalent AP stability without elbow restriction\n5. Better patient comfort, easier to adjust, less risk of elbow stiffness\n\n**POSITION**\n\u2022 Wrist: 10\xB0 flexion + ulnar deviation (dorsal displacement)\n\u2022 Forearm: neutral rotation\n\u2022 Elbow (sugar tong only): 90\xB0 flexion\n\n**PEARLS**\n\u2022 A+P eliminates the need to wrap around the elbow while maintaining AP stability\n\u2022 Sugar tong prevents pronation/supination \u2014 use when rotational control is critical\n\u2022 For Colles: mold the volar slab into slight flexion and ulnar deviation with 3-point pressure\n\u2022 Check capillary refill, sensation, and finger ROM after application\n\n**INSTITUTION NOTE**\nA+P splints preferred over sugar tong \u2014 no wrapping around elbow. [1][2]",
